xfr/-- 1. general programming info --

@node "howto_common"

  First of all a brief introduction of the implementation that is
  used for XFR.

  XFR data processing is structured in trees of objects. Each of
  these in a tree is structurally equal. xfr functions generate
  or modify object(s). there is one routine to kill a tree.

  The XFR system consists of functions of three categories.

   function             happening               purpose (example)

   --- managing --------------------------------------------------

    create    make a structure that is called   communicate info, 
	      "object" to handle a data         link related data
	      (this alltogether is an object)   together

	      the data is aquired on demand of a filename, a disk
	      drive number, a ram type or the rom
	      or may be supplied as a memory buffer

    frees     dismake structures, free memory   free all linked
					        data at once

    save      write data to file                save found module

   --- primary ---------------------------------------------------

    identify  set informational object fields   detect filetype;
              by recognizing format of a data   find errors

    scan      test every offset in a data,	rip module/data
	      find areas that have a format
	      and mark them by a branch(es)
	      of child object(s)

   --- special ---------------------------------------------------

    extract   mark areas in a module/data by    retrieve samples
	      a branch(es) of child object(s)   from a module

    patch     modify module/data of an object   reprogram replay

    convert   make independent object/tree      decrunch module;
	      with its own module/data buffer   change format

  Please consult the xfr.i besides this developer manual and do
  also view some program-side informations, especially the some
  notes on how to access XFR from programs, for a picture also
  when you "just" are about to make a client.
@endnode
xfr/-- 2. library routines for both programs and clients --
@node "malloc"

xfrMAlloc()

	DOES	Allocate a buffer of specified type and remember
		its size in order to free it with xfrMFree().

	GETS		d0	size	(advanced: xfrMemoryFlags|size)

	RETURNS		d0	*memory or NULL = failed

	USAGE		xfrMAlloc() buffers can only be freed with XFR
			funcs.

	SEE ALSO	xfrMFree(), xfrFreeObjects()

@endnode
@node "mfree"

xfrMFree()

	DOES	Free a buffer that had been allocated with
		xfrMAlloc() or xfrStringFormat().

	GETS		a1	*buffer

	RELATED		xfrMAlloc(), xfrStringFormat()

@endnode
@node "stringformat"

xfrStringFormat()

	DOES	Allocate and make a strign from a template and a
		value array as knowm from exec RawDoFmt()

	GETS		a0	*templatestring
			a1	*datastream

	USAGE		See exec.doc/RawDoFmt() for the formats of the
			input to this routine. You get a newly allocated
			and formated string which you may use, print or
			(for clients) store in xfrCom or an object. It's
			recommended to use this routine to make the
			information text for an object, which is usually
			then stored in xfrCom_text and the xfrFx_TEXTALLOC
			flag is set in xfrCom_flags. In an object the
			string will be freed automatically, if you needed
			it just for printing, free it with xfrMFree().
			

	RETURNS		d0	*newstring or NULL = no memory

	RELATED TO	xfrMFree(), exec/RawDoFmt()

@endnode
xfr/-- 3. program-side library routines --
@node "fixname"
xfrmaster.library/xfrFixName                   xfrmaster.library/xfrFixname

   NAME
	xfrFixName -- prefix + name + postfix into new or existing buffer

   SYNOPSIS
	string = xfrFixName(name, pcstyle, number, buffer, xfrFormat)
	d0                  d1    d2       d3      a1      a2

	STRPTR xfrFixName(STRPTR, BOOL, ULONG, APTR, struct xfrFormat *)

   FUNCTION
	You have got a pointer to an xfrFormat and a pointer to a module
	name (or else sort of data name). Pass the Format and name to
	xfrFixName and get a string built of that name with the prefix
	and postfix from the format. Optionally the destination buffer
	may be an existing one that you can pass in, too. This is optimal
	for to be used in conjunction with a filerequester. If not, pass
	buffer as NULL and get a newly allocated string that has just the
	size that it has plus a zero. This string must be freed with
	xfrMFree (while its equal what you do whit your own buffer).

  INPUTS
	name	  - pointer to a zero terminated ascii string, can be found
		    in xfrO_name or made custom e.g. when there is none
	pcstyle   - BOOL option to make fe. "name.mod" istead of "mod.name"
	number	  - normaly NULL or number (ULONG) for "mod.name (1)" etc
	buffer	  - pointer to a buffer that is long enough for at least
		    the resulting string plus a zero. except you want to
		    get a newly allocated string, then pass buffer as NULL.
	xfrFormat - pointer to an xfrFormat (can be found in xfrO_format),
		    you may pass NULL to add only a number but see notes

   RESULT
	string	  - this is either a pointer to your buffer same as passed
		    in, or its a pointer to a newly allocated string when
		    your passed in buffer has been NULL. The auto allocted
		    string can only be freed with xfrMFree(). In case of a
		    memory error NULL is returned.

   NOTES
	In the case where your object has got no name set and you need to
	use a default name, you may use the xfrB_defaultname from xfrBase.

	When your goal is to make saveable a just ripped module f.e. and
	you do not need to have the fixed name available for other purpo-
	ses, all default name handling and fixing can be completely done
	by xfrSaveObject().

	If you do only need to add a number and this is the only thing
	allways to do in that part of your code, rather use
	xfrStringFormat() with a template string like "%s (%ld)",0.

   SEE ALSO
	xfr/xfrMFree(), xfrSaveObject()

@endnode
@node "errortext"

xfrGetErrorText()

	DOES	Convert an XFR returncode into a human readable string.

	GETS		d0.w	returncode

	RETURNS		d0	*string

	USAGE		Errorcodes are all negative returncodes. A return
			value of NULL means simply no, not done, etc.
			A value of 1 means yes, success and similar.
			 See xfr.i for possible errors. After your program
			compared the returncode to needs, it may call
			this rotuine directly to get an explanation that
			can be shown to the user.
			 After every routine that creates new objects and/
			or after a scan or identification the xfrO_state
			field of the xfrObject structure may contain an
			error code (negative).

	RELATED TO	xfrO_state field in the xfrObject structure,
			all XFR rotuines that return codes/errors

@endnode
@node "create"

xfrCreateObject()

	DOES	Create an xfrObject structure for you, optionally with
		holding a buffer that is also created with a chooseable
		type of memory.

		Further it can load a file into that buffer for you and
		for a special, you may also get the chipmem, the fastmem
		or the rom as an xfrObject.

	GETS		d1	xfrOBJECT_... modes, see xfr.i

		optionally for mode xfrOBJECT_BUFFER

			d0	size	(advanced: xfrMemoryFlags|size)

		optionally for mode xfrOBJECT_FILE and xfrOBJECT_MINFILE

			d0	null	(advanced: xfrMemoryFlags)
			a0	*filename

		optionally for mode xfrOBJECT_DISK

			d0	drive number 0 to 3
				(advanced: drivenumber|xfrMemoryFlags)

	RETURNS		d0	*xfrObject

				or

				xfrERROR_MEMORY	    out of memory or
						    no fast memory for
						    xfrOBJECT_FASTMEM
				xfrERROR_DOS	    file read error
				xfrERROR_DISK	    disk/drive read error
				xfrERROR_NODISK	    not inserted

	USAGE		If you want to supply a buffer yourself, use
			xfrOBJECT_EMPTY and put the address of your
			buffer into xfrO_start.

			If you want XFR to free your buffer later
			when freeing the object,

				either have been using xfrMAlloc()
				for the buffer
				
				or exec AllocMem() and put the
				alloc-size in xfrO_buffersize
				(this is different from xfrO_size!)

			Custom buffers that were allocated in some other
			ways can NOT be freed by xfr and must be freed
			by the program. If these are the case, you also
			must set xfrO?_SHARED in xfrO_flags of the object
			where you attach a custom buffer to. To free your
			own buffer i recommend you not to rely on
			xfrO_start and xfrO_size. Better keep track of
			the correct address by yourself and may have the
			size stored in xfrO_buffersize (or elsewhere).
			The field xfrO_custom may allways be freely used
			by the program (its your own decision how you do
			use it or not).

			Do only use xfrFreeObjects() to free an xfrObject.

	SEE ALSO	xfrFreeObjects()

@endnode
@node "save"

xfrSaveObject()		-- NO tags here (XFRVERSION < 2 compatibility)
xfrSaveObjectTagList()	-- with a taglist
xfrSaveObjectTags()	-- varargs stub for xfrSaveObjectTagList()

	DOES	Write the data buffer of an object to a file.
                Files of same name are overwritten

	GETS		a1	*xfrObject

			a0	*filename or NULL to use the name of
				the object or a default name

				(may be left unitialised if the tag
				 XFR_FILENAME is passed)

		the tag using variant additionally gets

			a2	pointer to taglist

	RETURNS		d0	for xfrSaveObjectTags():

				xfrRETURN_NO = NULL -> file exists 

				(the tagless function does allways
				overwrite existing files)

				for both:

				xfrRETURN_YES = 1 -> succesfully saved

				(errors are negative values)

				xfrERROR_DOS
				xfrERROR_OBJECT if xfrO_size is missing

	NOTES	With the tags defined for this func in xfr.i you can do
		some things like adding proper postfix to the name or a
		number if the named file exists. The XFR_FILENAME tag if
		passed does override anything sent in a0, thus then you
		may leave a0 uninitialised. the name in a0 is left out-
		side the tags for compatibility and convenience, beeing
		the only parameter that would typically change in a stan-
		dard multiple usage of this routine from a same prog. so
		the taglist may be made global or constant.

		You can do a separate name fixing with xfrFixName() if
		you need to have the fixed name available.

   SEE ALSO
	xfr/xfr.i, xfrFixName()

@endnode
@node "freeobjects"

xfrFreeObjects()

	GETS		a1	*xfrObject

	USAGE		This does free the object with all linked next
			and child objects and all related infos.

			May NOT be use on objects that are nexts or
			childs to annother object. Does only work
			for objects that are first/root. Trying else
			can cause a crash with a not obvious reason.

			Per default it will also free the data buffers
			within (the loaded file, the module, etc), except
			xfrOB_SHARED in xfrO_flags is set. This f.e. is
			the case if YOU did set it because YOU allocated
			the buffer in some way custom to xfr.

			If you want to keep a buffer that was allocate by
			XFR, but the object node to be freed, do set the
			xfrOB_SHARED bit in xfrO_flags before calling
			xfrFreeObjects() and free the buffer later either
			with xfrMFree() (if xfrO_buffersize was null) or
			with exec FreeMem() (if there was the alloc size
			in xfrO_buffesize). Do only set the bit just
			before calling xfrFreeObjects().

		    !!! Do not free or detach a buffer from an object
			before freeing the object.

	SEE ALSO	xfrCreateObject()

@endnode
@node "identify"

xfrIdentify()

	DOES	Test an object buffer to be a supported type of data.
		If so, the object structure will be filled with
		available informations to that data.

	GETS		a1	*xfrObject
			d1	xfrMODE_..., see xfr.i

	RETURNS		d0	xfrRETURN_YES	its a supported format
				xfrRETURN_NO	unknown to XFR
				xfrERROR_... (negative), see xfr.i

	USAGE		I recommend to allways use with xfrMODE_DEEP here.

			See xfr.i/xfrObject for what information you
			may read out of an identified object.

			If this routine was successful on an object,
			you may use other routines on that object to
			do something with it. See section 5 belowst.

			The object must have been created before
			by xfrCreateObject() or by other xfr features
			or functions.

			The returnvalue is also stored in the field
			xfrO_state if it relates to the object.

@endnode
@node "scan"

xfrScan()

	DOES	Scan an object buffer to contain supported types
		of data. If so, these found datas will be marked
		by childobjects that are created for the scanned
		object. These child objects will contain available
		information on the data ranges they mark.

	GETS		a1	*xfrObject
			d1	xfrMODE_..., see xfr.i

			optional for xfrMODEF_HOOK

			a2	*hookcode
			d2	*hookdata

	RETURNS		d0	NULL -> scan ready
				xfrRETURN_SCANSTOP
				xfrERROR_... (negative), see xfr.i

	USAGE		The object must have been created before
			by xfrCreateObject() or by other xfr features
			or functions.

			After a scan or stopped scan:

			Get child objects from xfrO_firstchild, then
			in the child continue with xfrO_next.

			The field xfrO_firstchild of the main object
			is empty if the scan did not find anything.

			The child objects will contain information
			allways, even if the field xfrO_state of a
			child object is negative = errorcode. So in
			some cases you can see what exactly went
			wrong, where in memory and in which client.
			Though, the informations now may be incomplete
			or corrupt and this object is more like just
			an error notification than a found module.
			For debugging and improving more tricky
			riproutines, this feature comes in handy.

			If, as supposed to be, the routine was
			successful, the xfrO_state field of a child
			contains xfrRETRUN_YES = 1.
			Then you may use other routines on that object
			to do something with it. See section 5 belowst.

			If you use one of these routines on an non-
			successful child, you will get xfrERROR_OBJECT.

			The main object, the one you scanned,
			is not touched itself (yet).

			You may NOT free a child object or any other
			subsequent object by yourself. This is done
			automatically when you free the main object
			that you did create. This is the reason why
			xfrFreeObjects() is called ...s() plural.

			The xfrRETURN_SCANSTOP was sent by the hook,
			if any. The hook is a simple routine that
			has access to xfrCom.

			The hook can perform some things, f.e. check
			for break by user.

		Hook gets:

				d0	xfrRETURN_NO

				d1	state of last created child object,
					usually xfrRETURN_NO = NULL means
					no object at this position,
					xfrRETURN_YES or xfrERROR_... means
					there was something at this adress

				a0	*current_pos

					(an object that has just been found
					may and can have a different start)

				a4	*xfrCom
				a5	*xfrFormat current format
				a6	*xfrBase

		hook returns:	d0	xfrRETURN_NO -> continue
					xfrRETURN_SCANSTOP
					xfrERROR_...

		hook may kill:	d1-d5 / a0-a2


			'continue':

			When xfrScan() returns xfrRETURN_SCANSTOP, the
			position where we are now in memory is stored
			in xfrO_position of the scanned object. You may
			change that adress before calling xfrScan()
			again to continue where you want. You may set
			xfrO_position even before the first time you
			call xfrScan().

			The hook can test the last state which it gets
			in d1 and if its not xfrRETURN_NO (=NULL), the
			scan has just found something. The hook now can
			abort the scan and the program may report the
			findings. then the user may select continue
			in the program f.e.

			Of course reporting my also be done from the hook
			itself or as i do, after the complete scan, and
			then for all found things, one after annother.

@endnode
@node "extract"

xfrExtract()

	DOES	Extract contents (usually samples) from data and makes
		for them child objects to the object on which this func
		is used.

		Not to misunderstand, this extraction has nothing to do
		with unpacking or decrunching here. xfrExtract() is but
		for "marking the places" where the samples or other sub
		datas are in a file.

		Its more like a "getInfo" than an active function.

		Packed tracker modules may be converted with xfrConvert().

	GETS		a1	*xfrObject

	RETURNS		d0	xfrRETURN_NO (=NULL)	nothing to extract
				xfrRETURN_YES (=1)	extracted content(s)
				xfrERROR_... (negative) see xfr.i

	USAGE		The object must have been fully successfully
			associated with a format by XFR somehow before
			in order to use this function on it. If not,
			you get an xfrERROR_OBJECT returned and no
			extraction happened.

			You will get an xfrERROR_FORMAT if the associated
			format does not support extraction.

	SEE ALSO	xfrConvert()

@endnode
@node "patch"

xfrPatch()

	DOES	Patches the data that is hold by the object on which
		this func is used.

	GETS		a1	*xfrObject

	RETURNS		d0	xfrRETURN_NO (=NULL)	nothing to patch
				xfrRETURN_YES (=1)	patched
				xfrERROR_... (negative) see xfr.i

	USAGE		The object must have been fully successfully
			associated with a format by XFR somehow before
			in order to use this function on it. If not,
			you get an xfrERROR_OBJECT returned and no
			patching done to it.

			You will get an xfrERROR_FORMAT if the associated
			format does not support patching.

			After a patch the flag xfrO?_MODIFIED is set!

@endnode
@node "convert"

The convert in difference to patch does not modify the original datas,
but generates at least one annother object with its own buffer.

xfrConvert()

	DOES	Convert the module or something that is in the buffer
		of an xfrObject to a more common format. To annother
		format which usually is of a more common usual type.
		For example this is decrunching packed tracker mods.
		xfrConvert() does allways genearte at least one
		annother object with its own buffer containing the
		new made module/datas. xfrConvert() does never modify
		the original data.

	GETS		a1	*xfrObject

	RETURNS		d0	*new_xfrObject (YOU need to free it)

				or xfrRETURN_NO	(=NULL) nothing to convert
				   xfrERROR_... (negative), see xfr.i

	USAGE		The object must have been fully successfully
			associated with a format by XFR somehow before
			in order to use this function on it. If not,
			you get an xfrERROR_OBJECT returned and no
			patching done to it.

			After a successful conversion you get the results
			as a pointer to a newly created annother xfrObject
			that holds a new buffer with the converted data.

			You (your program) must free that object with
			an extra call to xfrFreeObjects().

			The new object is supposed to allready contain
			via XFR available information when you get it
			given to you. You do not need to xfrIdentify()
			it. Though, in some cases maybe you might want
			to use the other XFR-functions on it.

	SEE ALSO	xfrFreeObjects()

@endnode
@node "extscan"

xfrExtScan()

	NOT YET IMPLEMENTED

	USAGE		For the hook see xfrScan().

@endnode
xfr/-- 4. in-client routines --
@node "clients" "the machines: in-client routines"

If you make a client, these are the routines for
the functions that can be supported. There is no
need for a function to be supported.

	primary functions

	XFR_CHECK     , @{" recognition routines " Link "checkers"}
	XFR_SCAN      , ..
	XFR_DEEPSCAN  , ..
	XFR_DEEPCHECK , ..

	secondary functions

	XFR_EXTRACT   , @{" extractor " Link "extractor"}
	XFR_CONVERT   , @{" converter " Link "converter"}
	XFR_PATCH     , @{" patcher " Link "patcher"}
	XFR_EXTSCAN   , @{" extra scanner " Link "extrascanner"}

To the left is the tag with which you may build the
function into a format from the format tags.
@endnode
@node "checkers"

XFR can differentiate 4 recognition routines. There is no need to
support any of them (if no one is present, the format is suspended
as long no other format does share or import it in some way).

XFR_CHECK		<- primary
XFR_DEEPCHECK
XFR_SCAN		<- primary
XFR_DEEPSCAN

The checkers are used by xfrIdentify() simply on the start of a file,
the scanners are used by xfrScan() on each even address of a file.
(except with xfrMODE?_ODD on nowadays processors the scan does every addi) 

In the xfrMODE?_DEEP only the deep routines are engaged.

But in the normal mode (default) and the xfrMODE?_HYBRID the following
steps are what happens:

	1. it is checked wether XFR_MAGIC#? matches or not
	   (at xfrIdentifiy() start+XFR_OFFSET is checked,
	   while in xfrScan() the offset is substracted
	   from the current position after a succesful return
	   from a recognition routine to get the start)
	2. when it matched or when it is not defined, the
	   primary routine is called

In the xfrMODE?_HYBRID a third step is done in addition, when nothing
has been recognized until now:

	3. when the primary routines of _all_ active formats
	   of _all_ clients have not proven a module or data to
	   be there until now, in the xfrMODE?_HYBRID the deep
	   routines are engaged, too

	   Here you may code tests that either take much more
	   time or just test for very rare occurences, which
	   is also rather handled in this internal deep pass.

Though, by all means, the XFR_DEEPCHECK is for convenience. It is
simply not needed in allmost any case, except there is a way to
recognize f.e. a raw sample, what would take relatively very much time.

In any other and far more common case please consider the following two
tips, before you go on to the routine details:

- I highly recommend to use the same routine by the primary checker and
the primary scanner if this is possible. It does make programming efforts
few and is the main case why I invented the XFR_OFFSET tag. The reason
then for having separate routine tags is still to make a program to
understand which methods a format does support.

- If there is a deep scanner, too (may take some more time), I recommend
to use that routine also for the _primary_ _checker_ (some more time at
xfrIdentify() is ok and switching between deep and flat mode there has
rarely a relieving effect). See my note on XFR_DEEPCHECK above.

Think through and decide what is the best combi for your format.

All XFR format recognition routines share the same interface:


	you get:	d0	NULL (=xfrREUTRN_NO)

				may use d0 for whatever you want. if left
				as is, this indicates nothing found.

			a0	*start of data to test

				in details this is aka

				check,deepcheck: start of file
				           scan: current_pos - XFR_OFFSET
						 (routine is only called
						 when it comes in range;
						 combined with the offset
						 and magic implementation
						 this is fuck more faster
						 than any other solutions,
						 especially when part of
						 your client written in c)
				       deepscan: current pos

			a4	*xfrCom
			a5	*xfrFormat current format
			a6	*xfrBase

	you may kill:	d1-d5 / a0-a2

	you return:  d0		xfrRETURN_NO	nothing found
				xfrRETURN_YES	(=1) found
				xfrERROR_...	see xfr.i


	what you do in an XFR recognition routine:

Prove the presence of a format and if it is there, do retrieve and
calculate informations on the data and write these into xfrCom. Then
set a return value or error code into d0 and return.

		in details:

		In most cases the start address is just must neither
		calculated, nor set nowhere. Its done automated by XFR.

		In the XFR_?SCAN routines it may be that a true start
		is found. Only then write that to xfrCom_start.

		Write a size to xfrCom_size when you can calculate it.
		(have been put xfrFF_SIZE into XFR_FLAGS tag at the
		format tags)

		The xfrCom_end field for convenience is optional
		instead of xfrCom_size.

		If you are very sure, that your calcualted size _is_ de-
		finitely a size and is correct (format mus must have been
		very securely recognized), then you may compare it against
		xfrCom_MemEnd-your_start and return anxfrERROR_MISSINGEND
		to signal there are really bytes missing at the end of
		the file. Any other sizes that you return are checked by
		XFR and eventually one of the codes xfrERROR_SIZELARGER
		or xfrERROR_SIZENEGATIVE is set. Do not set these two by
		yourself. They are amibigous in meaning and only for
		emergency cases and debugging. XFR itself cannot
		distinguish an incorrectly calculated size from a really
		truncated file.

		You may put a pointer to a name and one to a info text
		in xfrCom_name and xfrCom_text. If you allocated one
		of these strings (whenever, do with xfrMAlloc() or
		xfrStringFormat()), you need to set the corresponding
		xfrO?_????ALLOC bits in xfrO_flags. Leave bits clear if
		the strings are part of your client or the generated
		module/data. (have been put the corresponding xfrFF_#?
		flag into the XFR_FLAGS tag at the format tags)

		In allmost any case the recognized format is logically
		just the same than the one where your recognition
		routine is called from. XFR does know this and then you
		must _not_ write xfrCom_format. In other cases,

		to get the pointer to a format that is private to your
		client you have been using the XFR_FORMATPTR tag with
		that format. To import the pointer to annother format
		that is supported by the lib or by annother client you
		have been using the XFRCLIENT_IMPORTLIST feature of your
		xfr client (to import one or more formats).

		You need to write a start into xfrCom_start only when it
		is different from the one you have got in a0. You may
		search for a real start only between xfrCom_MemStart and
		xfrCom_MemEnd, but you must not in any case prove the
		final value to be inside the range when you just calcu-
		lated it. XFR does this anyway and eventually sets an
		xfrERROR_START. Do just compare the calculated start
		against xfrCom_MemStart when you know it _is_ correct and
		maybe before the a0 that you have got. Then return
		xfrERROR_MISSINGSTART.

		After writing into xfrCom is ready for a single content
		(e.g. a single sample), call xfrResult(). From there XFR
		makes a child object with your values to the processed
		object and then reinitialises the xfrCom structure.

		When extractor routine returns, put one return value in
		d0, xfrRETURN_YES when extracted, xfrRETURN_NO when there
		was nothing to extract (comes by default in d0 to your
		extractor also) or xfrERROR_#? when something went wrong.

You do not need to set d0 to xfrRETURN_NO if you don't touch d0 at all.


assmebler programmers footnote:

The fastest method for a testroutine in 68k asm is (simplified) to do
the short branch only if a _rarely_ expected situation _did_ match:

				cmp.w	#$xxxx,yy(a0)
				beq.b	.yes
				rts
			.yes	moveq	#xfrRETURN_YES,d0
				rts
@endnode
@node "extractor"

xfrF_extract

	you get:     d0		xfrRETURN_NO (=NULL)

			a0	*xfrO_start
		     d1		xfrO_size
			a2	*xfrObject
			a4	*xfrCom
			a5	*xfrFormat current format
			a6	*xfrBase

	you may kill:	d1-d7 / a0-a3

	you return:  d0		xfrRETURN_NO	nothing to extract
				xfrRETURN_YES	extracted
				xfrERROR_...	see xfr.i

	what you do in xfrF_extract:

		For each content (usually a sample) you fill the
		certain fields of xfrCom which you get with a4 and
		then call xfrResult().

		in details:

		Fill in a start address to xfrCom_start and a size to
		xfrCom_size. The xfrCom_end field for convenience is
		optional instead of xfrCom_size.

		You may put a pointer to a name and one to a info text
		in xfrCom_name and xfrCom_text. If you allocated one
		of these strings (whenever, do with xfrMAlloc() or
		xfrStringFormat()), you need to set the corresponding
		xfrO?_????ALLOC bits in xfrO_flags. Leave bits clear if
		the strings are part of your client or the generated
		module/data.

		To get the pointer to a format that is private to your
		client you have been using the XFR_FORMATPTR tag with
		that format. To import the pointer to annother format
		that is supported by the lib or by annother client you
		have been using the XFRCLIENT_IMPORTLIST feature of your
		xfr client (to import one or more formats).

		After writing into xfrCom is ready for a single content
		(e.g. a single sample), call xfrResult(). From there XFR
		makes a child object with your values to the processed
		object and then reinitialises the xfrCom structure.

		When extractor routine returns, put one return value in
		d0, xfrRETURN_YES when extracted, xfrRETURN_NO when there
		was nothing to extract (comes by default in d0 to your
		extractor also) or xfrERROR_#? when something went wrong.

	SEE ALSO	xfr.i, xfrResult(),
			xfrMAlloc(), xfrStringFormat()

@endnode
@node "converter"

This is for converting data into annother, usually more common format.
The converter engines may be typically used to generate a generic
tracker module from a packed one. The other lesser typical case is to
generate a special custom playerheader format. Further conversions are
also welcome. For now every format can have one possible conversion,
except you pop up a choice requester... (i am interested in a solution
how xfr could support alternate conversions)

The convert in difference to patch does not modify the original datas,
but generates at least one annother object with its own buffer.


xfrF_convert

	you get:     d0		xfrRETURN_NO (=NULL)

			a0	*xfrO_start
		     d1		xfrO_size
			a2	*xfrObject
			a4	*xfrCom
			a5	*xfrFormat current format info
			a6	*xfrBase

		The xfrCom structure you get here is allmost empty
		except of xfrCom_MemStart and xfCom_MemEnd marking the
		boundarys of the buffer in which the object is. The
		object may be somewhere in that buffer and has not
		neccessarily the same start address nor size.

		Also xfrCom_Object contains *xfrObject. The rest of the
		xfrCom structure here is empty and must NOT be used.

	you may kill:	d1-d7 / a0-a3

	you return:  d0		*new_xfrObject

				or xfrRETURN_NO		nothing to convert
				   xfrERROR_...		see xfr.i

	what you do in xfrF_convert:

		Usually you allocate a buffer, convert the data from
		the buffer of the xfrObject you have got into your
		buffer and then if successfull create a NEW xfrObject
		and put your new buffer into it. Surely you may choose
		annother order of steps. Then, as your new object
		should contain available information also, make an
		xfrIdentify() on it or (if the new format is not
		identified by xfr or its really something special) do
		set up the object fields by yourself like this:

		Fill in a start address to xfrO_Start and a size to
		xfrO_size. You may put a pointer to a name and one
		to a info text in xfrO_name and xfrO_text. If you
		allocated one of these strings (whenever, do with
		xfrMAlloc() or xfrStringFormat()), you need to set
		the corresponding xfrO?_????ALLOC bits in xfrO_flags.
		Leave them clear if the strings are part of your
		client or the generated module/data. To get the
		pointer to a format that is private to your client
		you have been using the XFR_FORMATPTR tag with that
		format. To import the pointer to annother format that
		is supported by the lib or by annother client you
		have been using the XFRCLIENT_IMPORTLIST feature of
		your xfr client (to import one or more formats).

		When in the converted state there are two or more
		buffers to maintain (e.g. some files after conversion
		may consist of two files), you create two or more
		objects and link them either via xfrO_next when their
		contents are independent, or via the xfrO_firstchild
		(and then xfrO_next for even more parts) to signifiy
		they need to be saved together (when saved) and one is
		prior to the other(s). In that child-case you need to
		set xfrO?_EXTERN in the xfrO_flags of the child(s) to
		signal there is a buffer outside of the parent buffer.

		Return the pointer to the first/prior object that you
		generated in d0. If an object failed, set its state to
		an error code (see xfr.i). Only if any conversion
		failed, return an error code in d0.

	SEE ALSO	xfrMAlloc(), xfrStringFormat(), xfrIdentify()

@endnode
@node "extrascanner"
				n/i = not implemented

The xfrExtScan() ("ExtRipp()" in Eagleplayer) is not implemented yet.
It will be in future and variables then will be communicated through a
custom client specific structure of which each rip in progress will get
its own (by attatching to xfrObject). Sorry, maybe no tfmx sample now.
@endnode
@node "patcher"

	a client can provide a function to modify a module or anyhting
	else waht you ripped or have loaded from disk

	sometimes this is necessary, f.e. Ben Daglish, SidMon 1

	though, patching is optional as some people do want to rip
	untouched stuff


xfrF_patch

	you get:     d0		xfrRETURN_NO (=NULL)

			a0	*xfrO_start
		     d1		xfrO_size
			a2	*xfrObject
			a4	*xfrCom
			a5	*xfrFormat current format info
			a6	*xfrBase

		The xfrCom structure you get here is allmost empty
		except of xfrCom_MemStart and xfCom_MemEnd marking the
		boundarys of the buffer in which the object is. The
		object may be somewhere in that buffer and has not
		neccessarily the same start address nor size.

		Also xfrCom_Object contains *xfrObject. The rest of the
		xfrCom structure here is empty and must NOT be used.

	you may kill:	d1-d7 / a0-a3

	you return:  d0		xfrRETURN_YES		a patch was done

				or xfrRETURN_NO		nothing to extract
				   xfrERROR_...		see xfr.i

	what you do in xfrF_patch:

		If you have questions write to silva at psi5.com.

@endnode
xfr/-- 4a client side library routines --
@node "lib_clients" "the special routine xfrResult()"

		the special routine
		-------------------

		that is only used from/by the clients


xfrResult()

	you pass	a4-a6	as you've got them from the lib,
				so you just forward them

	returns		d0	if this is NEGATIVE, you have to
				abort your loop/routine and return
				this d0 to the lib

	This routine creates a new object from the data supplied in
	the certain fields of xfrCom (a4) and then attaches that object
	as a child to the main object (in xfrCom_object).
	Afterwards ALL certain fields of xfrCom are auto-cleared (!),
	so you will have to set them again even if they should have the
	same content as before.

@endnode
xfr/-- 5. some notes on accessing XFR from programs --
@node "howto_programs"

Please do let XFR allocate the memory for you. You may do it yourself if
you feel like you understand the specifications showed in this file and
in xfr.i .

The main consept is, that a so called >> xfrObject << holds a buffer of
memory with data to identify or to scan in it. Such an object is both
a list header AND a node. XFR does build trees ob xfrObjects in proceed
of a ripping process.

Look at the chart below to understand. We worked on a loaded file that
contains some modules. The second module has three samples and a
secondary part of data that should be saved to a separate file.

The downward ... represent the fields of an xfrObject structure, the
arrows show how they are linked or which object is what kind of thing.


After xfrScan():


	xfrObject                          <- the object that was scanned
	   ...
	   xfrO_firstchild -> xfrObject                   <- found Module
	   ...                   ...
				 ...
				 xfrO_next -> xfrObject   <- second
	                         ...             ...         found Module
	                                         ...
	                                         xfrO_next -> xfrObject
After xfrExtract():                               ...             ...
	                                         ...
	First sample ->             xfrObject <- xfrO_firstchild
	of the second                  ...       ...
	found Module                   ...
	                               ...
	Next sample ->    xfrObject <- xfrO_next
	                     ...       ...
	                     ...
	                     ...
	                     xfrO_next -> xfrObject       <- third sample
	                     ...             ...
	                                     ...
After xfrExtScan():                          ...
	                                     ...
	Separate replay-routine, ->          xfrO_next -> xfrObject
	Object has xfrOB_EXTERN bit                       ...
	set in xfrO_flags                                 ...


What we did to get the above was, call xfrScan() on an object. Then for
each of its found childs called xfrExtract() to get the samples. Then
also on each child called xfrExtScan() to get the separate replay
routines. After all work and saving of each subject with xfrSaveObject()
the whole tree can be free by a single call to xfrFreeObjects.
Wow, this is power. :)))))


The standard order of calling XFR-routines is:

	1.	make an xfrObject with xfrCreateObject(...),
		see function above and xfr.i for object types
	 2.	call xfrIdentifiy(mode, *xfrObject)
		see the results in the object xfrO_format, etc,
		call other functions on the object,
		see xfr.i for modes
	 2.a	call xfrScan(mode, *xfrObject)
	  2.a1	visit each child object if any and test its
		flags, eventually call xfrExtScan() or other
		functions on them
	3.	call xfrFreeObjects() frees all objects, except
		the output of conversion

	The Functions xfrSaveObject(), xfrExtract(), xfrExtScan(),
	xfrPatch(), xfrConvert() do only work for succeeded objects
	that passed xfrIdentify() or were created as childobjects to
	the input object by xfrScan(). Though, I guess xfrSaveObject()
	does allways work.

You may use and change the assembler sources examples to your needs.


Every time when you use an XFR routine on an xfrObject that has a
parent object (thus, usually on found data), xfr will look back in
the tree to the outermost parent object to know the possible memory
range. This is done especially by xfrExtScan(), because you use
xfrExtScan() on a found child object but it needs to scan the whole
buffer from which that child resulted. That buffer again is marked
by the parent object that had been scanned first by xfrScan() when
the child came from.

Further you must know that in some cases you may call such like
an xfrIdentify() or xfrScan(), which are the two big doors of XFR
also on a newly found child itself in recursion. If you do so, XFR
will look higher in the tree to the parent objects to find the
allowed memory range also.

For those who never used flagbits before, that were defined with BITDEF
in an assembler includefile, please look below. I'll show you an example
with the flagbit that marks an object as beeing external replay routine
or secondary data with own buffer.

	xfrO?_EXTERN

The ? may either be F or B. If it is F, the flag is meant. B means the
bit number of that flag.


  A NOTE TO HIGH LANGUAGE PROGRAMMER
  (excerpt from xfrmaster_lib.fd)

* attention: the two functions xfrSaveObject() and xfrSaveObjectTagList()
*            are physically DIFFERENT. the first takes NO tags nor lists
*            at all. To use the second func in varargs style, do make an
*            xfrSaveObjectTags() stub for it and take care on the tagless
*            older function entry to be unique whenever you create or use
*            tools to create pragmas from this fd. some progs dont do it.
@endnode
xfr/-- 6. some notes on writing XFR-clients --
@node "howto_clients"

If you are not suffered with the results a certain format ripper gives,
you may rewrite it on a basis of obtaining the source by asking the
author or obtaining informations from one of the various resources. May
check the links on the homepage. I will release some of my sources from
now and then. Yet some of my supplied clients make very flat checks and
may produce lots of unpleasant results when tested with ambigous data.

Within an XFR client can be a little variety of human readable infor-
mations. Please check out the colored examples on the homepage before
you do anything else. This is also good for all in all understanding.

You must NOT write a point "." before or after a suffix or prefix in
your formats definitions. The XFR library does add the points where
they are requestet wether the user wants an amiga or pc naming scheme.

Every allocation and linkage of objects from the clients view is done
by the library and programs. The clients do only communicate with the
library through the xfrCom structure. Details (and exceptions if any)
are explained at this guidefiles sections for the in-client routines.

If something can go wrong in a client routine that makes the rip or 
action improper, look up the xfrERROR_#? codes in the includes and set
them. When there is no XFR error code that fits, the xfrERROR_FAIL must
be used. Then also a pointer to a brief null terminated error text may
be put into xfrCom_info (can be xfrO_info in some cases).

If you are not suffered with the errorcode the master library sets on
your ripped object due to some values your client has set were illegal
or out of a range, do set a specific errorcode from the client after
checking vor legal vaules and ranges yourself. Normally this is done
by XFR automatedly but there are logic cases where you can know better. 

Your xfr client routines must all be re-entrant, useable from two or
more programs at the same time. So, self-modify code and task/module
specific temporary variables (e.g. samplesize) besides the code or in
annother hunk are strictly prohibited and may be not working either on
some amiga. When such temporary variables are needed, they must be put
on stack. But, real globals, e.g. pointers to shared xfrFormats (no
other globals I can think of are supported at this time) may be made
from the format tags (similar to "RPT_EagleBase",the_global) and used.
Put them into a bss hunk when more than a few. Is it needed to do that
anyway to guarantee working on a cached cpu?
@endnode
--
XFR eXternal Format Rippers
